(1, 1, 'A ''''shrimp woman'''' is any woman with a really ugly face, but with a hot body. We say that she''s a shrimp woman, because you can chop the head off and eat the rest of the body.', '- Puxa, a Claudinha é o maior camarão né?\n- [Só é].', 'Raimunda, Baranga', 'A', 'bruno@tupilabs.com', '2012-08-26 16:52:41', '2012-08-26 16:52:41', 'kinow', ''),
(2, 2, 'Any woman with a nice ass, but ugly face.', '- Lá vai a Raimunda! Feia de cara mas boa de bunda!', 'Baranga, Mulher camarão,gíria', 'A', 'bruno@tupilabs.com', '2012-08-26 17:01:41', '2012-08-26 17:01:41', 'kinow', ''),
(3, 3, 'An ugly woman.', '- O que você acha da Márcia?\n- Eu acho ela maior baranga.', 'Feiosa, Dragão', 'A', 'bruno@tupilabs.com', '2012-08-26 17:02:50', '2012-08-26 17:02:50', 'kinow', ''),
(4, 4, 'Coé is the shortened version of "[Qual é]". It is usually used in interrogative sentences.', '- [Eae], coé [mermão]?', 'Qual é', 'A', 'bruno@tupilabs.com', '2012-08-26 17:12:22', '2012-08-26 17:12:22', 'kinow', ''),
(5, 5, 'Same as Coé, but written correctly. The meaning is similar to wazup.', '- Eae, Qual é a boa?', 'eae, coé, beleza, blz', 'A', 'bruno@tupilabs.com', '2012-08-26 17:25:19', '2012-08-26 17:25:19', 'kinow', ''),
(6, 6, 'Has a similar meaning to English ''''Yo''''. In an informal conversation, it is easier to hear a Brazilian saying ''''Eae'''' rather than ''''Oi'''' or ''''Olá''''.', '- Eae, [beleza]?\n- [Opa], beleza, e você?', 'beleza, olá, yo', 'A', 'bruno@tupilabs.com', '2012-08-26 17:35:31', '2012-08-26 17:35:31', 'kinow', ''),
(7, 7, 'Shortened version of "Meu irmão", or my brother / my bro. Used to refer to somebody.', '- Eae mermão, beleza? (Yo bro, wassup?)', 'gíria,bro,brother,cara,brodi,mano,meu irmão', 'A', 'bruno@tupilabs.com', '2012-08-26 18:04:37', '2012-08-26 18:04:37', 'kinow', ''),
(8, 8, 'Same as "Get out". You can use this while you are talking with your friends, but it is not very polite. Probably, you wouldn''''t use"Cai fora" in a business meeting. Or after having dinner with a hot woman.', '- O jogo tá um lixo, vamo cair fora?', 'sair fora,sai fora,vazar', 'A', 'bruno@tupilabs.com', '2012-08-26 18:06:23', '2012-08-26 18:06:23', 'kinow', ''),
(9, 9, '"Beleza" literally means "Beauty". As in ''''Sua beleza me encanta. A sua voz e o teu calor!''''. \n\nHowever, it is very likely that you will hear more often "Beleza" being used with similar meaning to "Okay", "Okeydokey", "Cool" or as "How are you doing?".', '- [Eae], beleza? (Yo, how''s it going?)', 'de boa,tudo bom,suave,okay,fechou,fechô', 'A', 'bruno@tupilabs.com', '2012-08-26 18:08:35', '2012-08-26 18:08:35', 'kinow', ''),
(10, 10, 'Okay, this one can be very handy. Literally translating, it would be "Shitting and walking". But the meaning, is similar to "Water off a duck''s back".\n\nThere''s a pun with those Yogurts the makes your intestines work better and Johnnie Walker, as one makes you shit, and the other says to keep walking.\n\nIt is used to demonstrate that you don''''t care about something.', '- Ow, [cê] ouviu o que eles [tão] falando de você?\n- [Bah], [tô] cagando e andando mano.', 'gíria,tô nem aí,nem ligo,e o quico?,e o kiko?', 'A', 'bruno@tupilabs.com', '2012-08-26 18:11:08', '2012-08-28 01:13:56', 'kinow', 'kinow'),
(11, 11, 'Same as "bro". Some time ago, it would be seen as very rude. And even now you don''t hear may kids using "Mano" while talking to their parents. But you can use it interchangeably with "Cara" while talking with your lads.', '- Eae mano, [de boa]?\n- Opa, [suave na neve].', 'bro,brother,cara,bródi,mano brown', 'A', 'bruno@tupilabs.com', '2012-08-26 18:12:38', '2012-08-26 18:12:38', 'kinow', ''),
(12, 12, '"Cara" means "face" or "dude". When you want to talk about someone, you can use it in the same way you would use "Guy".', '- Quem é aquele cara? (Who''s that guy?)', 'bro,brother,cara,bródi,mano brown', 'A', 'bruno@tupilabs.com', '2012-08-26 18:14:15', '2012-08-26 18:14:15', 'kinow', ''),
(13, 13, '"Opa" is usually used in the beginning of sentences. It can mean ''''Sorry'''', if you use it after you have bumped in somebody. Or it can also be a compliment, like "Hello".', '- Opa, [beleza]?', 'bro,brother,mano,bródi', 'A', 'bruno@tupilabs.com', '2012-08-26 20:49:38', '2012-08-26 20:49:38', 'kinow', ''),
(14, 14, 'The translation of this expression is "Vulture in a war is chicken". It is used when you are in the end of a party, or when you are desperate for a girl. So any girl will look beautiful for you, or a vulture will look like chicken for you.', '- Pô, aquela [mina] é muito é feia!\n- Ah, mas urubu em guerra é frango né [velho]?', 'gíria,ditado,baranga', 'A', 'bruno@tupilabs.com', '2012-08-26 21:02:27', '2012-08-26 21:02:27', 'kinow', ''),
(15, 15, 'A "caralho" is a "dick". It is used in the same way that "shit" is used in English. Also known as "[caraleo]".', '- Gol da Argentina no Brasil! (narrator)\n- Caralho!', 'gíria,palavrão,NSFW', 'A', 'bruno@tupilabs.com', '2012-08-26 21:03:14', '2012-08-26 21:03:14', 'kinow', ''),
